<HEADLINE> Test would use brain activity to diagnose attention disorder  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) - A psychologist says he and a partner in
Tennessee may be on to a biological test for attention deficit
hyperactivity disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent J. Monastra of the FBI Attention Disorders Clinic in the
suburb of Endicott and Joel F. Lubar of the University of Tennessee
say the disorder can be diagnosed by monitoring activity in the
front region of the brain. They have developed a test they say is
90 percent effective.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration, it would
be the first laboratory procedure for diagnosing ADHD.
</P>
<P>
   ADHD is currently diagnosed according to a set of guidelines
written by the American Academy of Pediatrics.
</P>
